Hysham Volleyball Fan Procedures

2020 Season

Visiting fans:

Please enter through the multipurpose room doors off Elliott Street. Watch for signs.

Temperature checks and a contact tracing list will be compiled at the ticket table.

Please sit on the west side bleachers in the gym.

Please use concession stand in the multipurpose room.

Please use restrooms on west side of multipurpose room next to the Ag Shop. Signs will be posted.

Please social distance while watching the games, going to the restroom, or getting concessions.

Masks are not required, but are encouraged.

Please follow guidelines so we can continue to have fans at our games and our kids can keep playing.

post_text:
Here are some updates for our Fall Sports. Masks are required at all home and away games unless notified differently. We will not be serving concessions, so bring your own snacks. If you have purchased the family pass of $200, you will receive a code for the NFHS network that will be good for a calendar year from August 28. Contact Mr. Grabowska for the code. If you have not purchased it, you still have time. Any codes I have left after the family passes will be sold for $50.

Football: Fans will be able to attend our home games so far without limitations. Masks are required and we ask for social distancing between people and/or family groups. Please use the east end gate (closest to the school). Away games may be limited to 50 visiting fans-each games limits will be announced.

Volleyball: Seating will be limited for volleyball games to approximately 50 for the home team and 50 for visiting teams. There will be a sign up on the website for this. Again masks are required.

post_text: Like everything else now, our fall sports season is in the world of the unknown. At this point we have been given the go ahead by MHSA to run our fall seasons. Students will be asked to follow some specific protocols so that we can provide the safest environment possible. We do believe that extra-curricular activities are an integral part of the educational process that we can offer students. We will post game updates prior to all of our contests so that parents know what limitations may be in place for each game. We really want to stress the convenience of the NFHS Network in watching all junior high and high school games for this upcoming year. We are hoping to have a lower cost deal in place for the annual NFHS Network fee and will share that as soon as or if it becomes available.

Students will be asked to follow some specific protocols so that we can provide the safest environment possible. We do believe that extra-curricular activities are an integral part of the educational process that we can offer students. We will post game updates prior to all of our contests so that parents know what limitations may be in place for each game. We really want to stress the convenience of the NFHS Network in watching all junior high and high school games for this upcoming year. We are hoping to have a lower cost deal in place for the annual NFHS Network fee and will share that as soon as or if it becomes available.

As we have continued through the process of developing a reopening plan for Park City Schools, things have changed through research, recommendations, and other things, just as they have in other aspects of our lives. We still want to provide the best education possible for the children in our community. That includes being mindful of student safety, both physically and emotionally, developed curriculum that will meet state and national standards, meeting the post-secondary needs of our students so we can prepare them for college or the workplace, and providing opportunities for our students in co-curricular activities. In order to do the above, the following plan was approved by the board.

20-21 plans. The goal for the 2021 school year is to have as normal a school year as possible. Once we are closer to the start, the Office of Public Instruction, the Governor's office, and the County Health department will stipulate certain things that could impact how we operate. Our general thoughts are that we want things to be as normal as possible while being very mindful of student and staff safety and well being.

An extremely important thing to note is that if students are sick with coughs, stomach aches, any sort of fever, etc., they will NEED TO STAY HOME until symptoms are cleared up.

Thank you to those who filled out the survey for the upcoming year. Here is the draft plan for the upcoming school year. Please remember that it is a draft plan. It will be updated as we get closer to school. Some things may change, such as face mask requirements.

Draft Plan

post_text: At an emergency meeting Monday night, the Park City School Board made the decision to continue to provide distance learning only for the remainder of the school year. Parents and students will be provided more information later in May on how students will be checked out and how they will return books and equipment. Teachers will be communicating how they will wind down their classes by May 21. Graduation will still happen on May 17, but it will be on the football field with limited seating focused on direct families, but it will be streamed live on the NFHS network for free.

April 10 at 1:01 PM 路

Attention Stillwater County!

Updated Health Order
Re: Extension to Length of Duration.

Please acknowledge the Updated Health Order which includes the increased length of the order to coincide with Governor Bullocks Shelter-in-Place.

While Montana has reached a current number of 365 confirmed positive Covid-19 cases, Stillwater County remains at 1 confirmed positive case. On a national level, our country has doubled in number of positive covid cases in the last 8 days. Additionally, our U.S. deaths have increased by 11,000 in a short 8 days.

Given the above information, it is imperative that we work as a community to continue to work towards slowing the curve and slowing the spread. Continue practicing social distancing, constant hand washing and hand sanitizing, and utilizing curb side pick up and delivery for your essential needs.

post_text:
The Governor has extended the school closure through April 24. Please have students continue their hard work in online classes and packets.

School employees will be on a scheduled holiday Friday, April 10, and Monday, April 13. Meals will not be delivered nor available on those dates.

If you have not signed up yet for breakfast and lunch, which is free for all children in the district ages 0-18, please do so. The form can be found on the district and school pages of our website.

Please contact the teachers and/or the school if you have questions for us during this new school situation. If If you are finding that your student is struggling with the work load, with the isolation, or other issues, please let us know and we will do what we can to help or to find help.

Buses will deliver to those who live on the bus route. The routes will be running 2 hours later than normal in the morning to deliver both meals. So Bus #1 will have its first stop at 9:12 AM instead of 7:12. Bus #5 will have its first stop at 9:03 AM instead of 7:03. And Bus #4 will have its first stop at 9:00 AM instead of 7. Monday's packet transfer for grades K-3 went great. Thank you for all your patience and cooperation.

We understand that parents were not prepared for their students being home for weeks if not months during the school year. If you don't have necessary school supplies at home, please contact your teacher and we will work to try provide supplies on our packet days.

Please check on the school's website for key information that may not be included in Infinite Campus announcements.

We know that many of you have had your schedules with work altered. And many of you are having to work from home or hours may have changed so it is difficult to contact teachers or the school during the work day. If you are emailing or trying to contact teachers after normal school hours, please be patient in waiting for replies as they also are affected by this and are often trying to work with their own children in their classes.

We are still operating as if we are returning on March 30, but we are preparing for a longer shutdown if announced by the governor. Here are some key points to know:

Students should be working in their classes. Creating a good routine for your student at home is important in having a good distance learning experience.
Free and reduced meals are still available at this time at the school between 11 AM and 12:30 PM at the front door. Please fill out a Free and Reduced Meal application if your financial status has changed due to the coronavirus.
Chromebooks are still available to check out one per family at the high school office.
If you don't have internet connectivity and have to get it, keep your receipt as you may be reimbursed by the school for service during the shutdown.
Call or email the school with any questions.

Park City FFA
March 12 at 2:32 PM 路

State Convention Postponed!!!

After careful and substantial consideration regarding the impact that the coronavirus has and will continue to make, it has been determined that the best option is to suspend the 2020 State FFA Convention and CDE Days in Great Falls until further notice. This decision was made by representatives from the Montana FFA Association, MSU Ag-Ed Department, Montana Board of Trustees and the Montana FFA Foundation. This is obviously heartbreaking news and something that is unprecedented. At this point we were most interested in getting the word out to everyone. Currently, no plans are in place on the best way to move forward. Please wait to hear from state administrators regarding potential solutions.



Thanks for your understanding and patience.
